		<b>Comment By Brian Kenny, 12-13-05</b>
		<p>Rebecca Solnit's A Field Guide to Getting Lost contains some western landscape and ideas about use of wilderness</p>
		
		<b>Comment By secondtear, 12-13-05</b>
		<p>I heard an NPR interview today with Denver poet Robert Cooperman.   He read from his book The Widowâ€™s Burden.  It sounded fantastic!</p>
		
		<b>Comment By sherouse, 12-19-05</b>
		<p>Part One of Jared Diamond's _Collapse: How Societies Choose to Fail or Succeed_, is "Modern Montana," an extended analysis of the state and its current challenges. Montana figures also in some of the book's later chapters, particularly Part Four, "Practical Lessons."</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Paul Matteucci, 12-21-05</b>
		<p>OK Jenny.  These are probably good--but a little bit chick-ee I think.  Anything for real men?</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Jenny Shank, 12-22-05</b>
		<p>Paul,<br />
Actually, several of these books are of the hairy-chested variety, especially "The Tender Bar," which is all about men hanging out among men in a bar, talking about manly things and drinking like men.  <br />
<br />
And our you calling Ted Kooser, the nation's poet laureate, a chick?  Well, he's pretty skinny so you could probably take him in a fight, but his book definitely will appeal to men (I know because my mom sent a copy of it to each of her seven brothers and they all loved it). Though he isn't even a middleweight, Kooser does manly stuff in the book like constructing a new outhouse for himself because he prefers to relieve himself in the great outdoors.  If that isn't manly, I don't know what is.<br />
<br />
Also, I'm in the middle of reading this terrific new book by Reg Saner called "The Dawn Collector: On My Way to the Natural World."  I plan to do a full review of it in a few weeks, but basically, Saner writes about his experiences hiking in the Colorado wilderness, and there's none of that New Age-y mysticism of the natural world that would scare off some he-men such as yourself.  Saner writes about cougars, encounters with Boulder (human) nutcases, and just very specific, clear, brainy prose about the natural world.  This book is the second in the series "Center Books on the American West" published by the Center for American Places in Santa Fe.<br />
<br />
And if you were really manly, you'd be man enough to read a book written by a woman!  "Zorro" might appeal more to a feminine audience, but those other two should appeal to everybody.</p>
		
